[[Category:Lists of landforms of Scotland]]

The '''geology of [[Martinique]]''' originated from volcanic eruptions, but has different rocks than nearby Lesser Antilles volcanic island arc islands all of which formed in the last 40&nbsp;million years in the [[Cenozoic]]. A high-alumina [[basalt]] ranges from [[olivine]] basalt to [[tridymite]]-rich [[dacite]]. Calc-alkaline volcanic rocks are rich in [[hornblende]] and orthpyroxene [[andesite]], hornblende andesite and quartz-hornblende dacite are also common.<ref name="springer">{{cite web|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02597827?LI=true|title=Petrology of the volcanic rocks of martinique, West Indies|website=SpringerLink|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref> Mount Pelee is one of the most active Caribbean volcanoes with 20 eruptions in the last 5000 years. It also heats groundwater, generating hydrothermal eruptions at sulfur springs in 1751 and 1851.<ref name="sciencedirect">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/0377027389900292|title=Case study of a volcanic geothermal system, Mount Pelée, Martinique|website=ScienceDirect|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref><ref name="sciencedirect2">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0012821X7690145X|title=K-Ar geochronology of the Limestone Caribbees and Martinique, Lesser Antilles, West Indies|website=ScienceDirect|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref>
