'''Lesley Wyborn''' is an [[Australia]]n [[Earth science|geoscientist]] and [[geoinformatics]] specialist, with a focus in [[high performance computing]] for [[geography]] and online analytics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchers.anu.edu.au/researchers/wyborn-lai|title=Dr Lesley Wyborn - ANU|last=|first=|date=|website=Dr Lesley Wyborn|publisher=Australian National University|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref> She is an Adjunct Fellow at the [[Australian National University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com.au/citations?user=B4RT4Q4AAAAJ&hl=en|title=Lesley Wyborn - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com.au|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref>

== Early life and education ==
Lesley graduated from the [[University of Sydney]] in 1972 with a Bachelor of Science in [[geology]]. She graduated with 1st class honours. In 1973 she completed a Diploma of Education in science and mathematics at the [[University of Canberra]]. In 1978 she went on to complete a Doctor of Philosophy in geology and [[geochemistry]]) at the [[Australian National University]].

== Research and contributions ==
Wyborn has over 42 years in geoscience research and geoinformatics. She began her research career in geochemistry, focusing primarily on the geochemistry of [[granite]]s, [[ore deposit]]s and regional alteration systems. She begin using computers in her research in 1994. She determined the essential parts of different Australian mineral systems, and computationally modeled these parts to understand why or deposits form in certain places.<ref name="ANU">{{Cite web|url=https://researchers.anu.edu.au/researchers/wyborn-lai|title=Lesley Wyborn|last=Lesley|first=Wyborn|date=|website=Lesley Wyborn - ANU|publisher=Australian National University|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref>

Wyborn has played a major role in allowing geoscientists to use computers in research. She made contributions to the development of the [[GeoSciML|Geoscience Markup Language]] (GeoSciML), which allows  access to freely available geoscience data. She also led the development of the Open Geospatial Consortium<ref name="GSA">{{Cite web|url=http://www.geosociety.org/awards/15speeches/geoinfo.htm|title=Geological Society of America - 2015 Geoinformatics Award - Lesley Wyborn|website=www.geosociety.org|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref> She was the co-developer of the Australian Virtual Geophysics laboratory, which she worked on from 2012 to 2013.<ref name="GSA"/>

Lesley's current research involves developing the  NCI National Environmental Research Data Interoperability Platform (NERDIP) and the NeCTAR Virtual Geophysics Laboratory (VGL).<ref name="ANU"/>

