{{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Rigny | other_name = ''Rignys Bjerg'' | photo = | photo_caption = | elevation_m = 2734 | elevation_ref = | prominence_m = | prominence_ref = | map = Greenland | map_size = 200 | label_position = left | listing = [[List of mountains in Greenland]] | location = [[Sermersooq]], [[Greenland]] | range = | coordinates = {{coord|69|2|55|N|26|49|23|W|type:mountain_region:GL_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range_coordinates = | coordinates_ref = <ref name="cat"/> | first_ascent =2003<ref name="cat"/> }}
'''Mount Rigny''', {{lang-da|Rigny Bjerg}}, ''Rignys Bjerg'') is a mountain peak in East [[Greenland]].<ref name="cat">{{cite web | title = Catalogue of place names in northern East Greenland | publisher = Geological Survey of Denmark | url = http://www.geus.dk/publications/bull/nr21/nr21_p117-368.pdf3 | accessdate = 18 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="mapcarta">{{cite web|url=http://mapcarta.com/19186286|title=Rigny Bjerg|work=Mapcarta|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref> It is located in [[King Christian IX Land]], [[Sermersooq]] Municipality.
The mountain was named by [[Jules de Blosseville]], after French naval officer [[Henri de Rigny|Marie Henri Daniel Gauthier, comte de Rigny]] (1782–1835).<ref>[http://www.arktiskinstitut.dk/pdf/Oestgroenlands_stednavne_portefoelje_ver_1.pdf Løve, Jan - Østgrønlands stednavne - fra den første kortlægning: Blossevilles togt med "La Lilloise" i 1833. Arktisk Institut]</ref> ==Geography== Mount Rigny is the highest peak in a mountainous area east of the [[Sortebrae Glacier]] close to the [[Blosseville Coast]]. Reaching {{convert|2734|m|ft|abbr=on}},<ref name="GE">[[Google Earth]]</ref> Rigny Bjerg was marked on [[Jules de Blosseville]]'s map of 1833 which also contained a drawing of the mountain's profile as seen from the sea. The mountain was then identified by the 1895-96 [[Ingolf Expedition]] led by [[Carl Frederick Wandel|C.F. Wandel]], and its approximate position determined by the 1898–1900 [[Carlsbergfund Expedition to East Greenland]] led by [[Georg Carl Amdrup|G.C. Amdrup]].<ref name="mapcarta"/> This mountain's elevation and position are incorrect in the [[Defense Mapping Agency]] Greenland Navigation charts.<ref>[http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/onc/txu-pclmaps-oclc-8322829_d_16.jpg 1:1,000,000 scale Operational Navigation Chart, Sheet C-13]</ref>
In Rigny Berg there are routes popular with [[mountaineer]]s, such as "Snow Falcon",<ref>[http://www.rockclimbing.com/routes/Europe/Denmark/Greenland/Rignys_Bjerg/Rignys_Bjerg/Snow_Falcon_48082.html Rockclimbing - Snow Falcon - WI3]</ref> as well as neighboring peaks in the region such as RHARPeak.<ref>[http://www.rockclimbing.com/routes/Europe/Denmark/Greenland/Rignys_Bjerg/Rignys_Bjerg/RHARPeak_48106.html Rockclimbing - RHARPeak]</ref> After a failed attempt in 1998, the first full ascent of the peak was made on 19 July 2003 by the 'Midnight Sun 03 Expedition'.<ref name="cat"/>
Certain studies claim that the mountain corresponds to the legendary [[Norsemen]]'s '''Blåsærk'''<ref>"Blue Shirt" - probably a descriptive name alluding to a dark appearance towering over the white inland ice, cf [[Hvitserk]].</ref> and to the '''Mount of Gods Mercie''' named by [[Henry Hudson]] in 1607.<ref>{{cite book | last=Tornøe |first =Johannes Kristoffer |year = 1964| title = Early American history: Norsemen before Columbus | place= London | publisher= Allen & Unwin | pages= 126}}</ref> {| |- valign="top" |[[File:Operational Navigation Chart C-13, 3rd edition.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Defense Mapping Agency]] map of Greenland sheet.]] |}
